00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:39.299
So I see Trang had asked a question during the demo, and it was, if I have two themes,

00:04:39.299 --> 00:04:43.619
dark and light, would I need to use two brand.yaml files?

00:04:43.619 --> 00:04:44.619
So...

00:04:44.619 --> 00:04:45.619
Garak?

00:04:45.619 --> 00:04:51.940
Well, I was going to say, this is a great question, and it also depends a little bit

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.179
on how each...

00:04:55.179 --> 00:04:58.660
The tool that you're using, how it implements light and dark themes.

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:03.820
So there's a different answer for Shiny and for Cordo, and I'll let Carlos talk first

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:06.260
about how Cordo works with this.

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:07.260
Right.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:13.899
So let me just start by saying that I think Cordo's light and dark mode support leaves

00:05:13.899 --> 00:05:19.380
quite a bit to be improved that we are working on 1.7, and so I'll give you the answer for

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:25.380
1.6, and things might change a little bit and become more convenient when we release

00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:27.140
1.7.

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:31.380
Brand.yaml promises we're still actively working on it, but we expect there to be improvements.

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:38.420
So for Cordo, it is probably easier for you to just use two themes, one for dark and one

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:43.339
separate brand.yaml file for dark, and one separate brand.yaml file for light.

00:05:43.339 --> 00:05:50.179
They work kind of like actual themes, if you're doing, like, theme configuration on Cordo,

00:05:50.179 --> 00:05:53.980
so you can just use those, and that's easier to do.

00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:59.059
The brand.yaml specification, if you go on the documentation, does include support for

00:05:59.059 --> 00:06:03.299
light and dark mode, but Cordo currently doesn't work with that.

00:06:03.299 --> 00:06:08.100
So the easiest way to do it is to just use two brand.yaml files.

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:12.660
But like Jarek will say, the answer for Shiny is a little bit different, so I'll let you

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:13.660
answer that.

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:14.660
Yeah.

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:21.019
So Shiny has a bit of a different approach to light and dark themes.

00:06:21.019 --> 00:06:27.220
This is also relatively recent in the sense that Bootstrap 5.3, which is the thing that

00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:34.299
the web framework and CSS sort of styling framework that Shiny uses, came out with a

00:06:34.299 --> 00:06:42.100
feature for native dark mode, and that was in Bootstrap 5.3, so that's a relatively recent

00:06:42.100 --> 00:06:48.859
thing that we've added in Shiny, and it came after Cordo had implemented their version

00:06:48.859 --> 00:06:50.579
of light and dark.

00:06:50.579 --> 00:06:55.299
So the way that Shiny approaches dark themes, or themes in general, is that you create one

00:06:55.299 --> 00:06:56.500
theme.

00:06:56.500 --> 00:07:00.899
That theme typically works best if you create the light theme, the light sort of variant

00:07:00.899 --> 00:07:07.660
of the theme, and then Bootstrap will automatically make a dark theme for you out of the colors

00:07:07.660 --> 00:07:08.940
that you've picked.

00:07:08.940 --> 00:07:13.899
So in Shiny, you can use a regular brand.yaml file.

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:24.299
If you target brand.yaml towards a light theme, then you can add the dark mode switch

00:07:24.299 --> 00:07:29.380
component into your app and get a dark mode theme for free.

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:32.100
Thank you.

00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:36.459
There was a kind of follow-on question to this one too, and it was, what about local

00:07:36.459 --> 00:07:37.459
fonts?

00:07:37.459 --> 00:07:42.660
How can I point brand.yaml to the local font files?

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:49.859
So again, the answer will be a little bit different from Cordo and Shiny, but in Cordo,

00:07:49.859 --> 00:07:56.179
we sort of, if you go on the brand.yaml documentation, there's three ways, two and a half ways, let's

00:07:56.179 --> 00:08:03.059
call it, of doing fonts, and the default one is an online font foundry is the name of it,

00:08:03.059 --> 00:08:08.700
like the website, and we use Google Fonts by default, but you can use a different CDN

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:12.940
that's more privacy friendly, or you can also use local fonts, and so if you just search

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:16.980
for fonts and search for the word source, that's where you get the fonts from, and then

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:19.940
you can point to the local font files.

00:08:19.940 --> 00:08:24.299
In Cordo, those, when you point them, they need to be inside the project, like all the

00:08:24.299 --> 00:08:29.059
other resources in Cordo, so that if you put them on GitHub and things stay reproducible,

00:08:29.059 --> 00:08:35.539
but you can definitely use local font files in that way, and if they are OTF files, they

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:40.859
will even work in Typed, for example, so you can use that as a system font for your

00:08:40.859 --> 00:08:46.460
PDF documents using Typed, so you can definitely do that, it's just the font specification

00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:51.059
needs to say that it's a local font, it's a system font, I think is how we call them,

00:08:51.059 --> 00:08:55.940
and then you just give the path to it, so you have to have the files.

00:08:55.940 --> 00:08:59.700
So there are actually two, you can have system fonts, or ones that are installed on your

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:05.380
system just anywhere on your system, you know, like if you, you know, you download

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:10.219
a font and then install it, like through either Windows or through macOS or whatever, and

00:09:10.219 --> 00:09:16.340
there's also local, which is, we intend to be, essentially, you go get the font files

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:22.260
and you're going to put them next to your brand.yaml file, and then we'll use those

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:29.020
files, so there are, so it is possible to use local fonts, and the brand.yaml website

00:09:29.020 --> 00:09:32.820
is a good reference for how to get that set up.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:35.619
Awesome, thank you.

