00:11:41.900 --> 00:11:46.619
Is there a way to use brand.yaml for ggplot?

00:11:46.619 --> 00:11:48.260
This is an excellent question.

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:53.340
So it gives me a little bit of a chance to explain the relationship between brand.yaml

00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:55.940
files and the other projects.

00:11:55.940 --> 00:12:02.020
So brand.yaml is not a feature of a specific software.

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:09.020
It's kind of like a specification that Garek and I developed was sort of how we think these

00:12:09.020 --> 00:12:12.820
other applications should understand in order to do their theming, right?

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:17.659
So someone somewhere needs to teach ggplot about how to do these.

00:12:17.659 --> 00:12:21.580
If you go sort of, you know, and use Python tooling, this would be like someone needs

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:27.859
to teach Matplotlib how to understand brand.yaml and those, and that hasn't been done yet.

00:12:27.859 --> 00:12:28.859
We are working on it.

00:12:28.859 --> 00:12:32.780
I don't want to give a promise for when these things are going to be sort of ready, but

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:37.340
this is something we're definitely working in 2025, and we have prototypes, and we're

00:12:37.340 --> 00:12:41.020
trying to understand sort of like how to make that really nice.

00:12:41.020 --> 00:12:46.500
But the hope is very much so that, you know, if it's not ggplot directly, it's some other

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:50.419
downstream library like thematic in the case of ggplot, for example, that knows how to

00:12:50.419 --> 00:12:56.580
configure a lot of different graphics for themes and teach thematic how to do brand.yaml

00:12:56.580 --> 00:13:01.780
configuration, and then you can very easily go from this one file and configure your document

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:03.979
and configure your plotting libraries.

00:13:03.979 --> 00:13:09.460
So that is not ready for sort of like public consumption, but we are actively working on

00:13:09.460 --> 00:13:10.460
it.

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:16.419
It will come out sooner rather than later, like just I don't want to give a promise of

00:13:16.419 --> 00:13:20.700
a date that might be pushed back, but we're on it.

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:26.500
I do want to follow up and say, though, that thematic is amazing, and it was one of my

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:33.419
favourite parts of working on the R side of things was realising that if we taught BSLib

00:13:33.419 --> 00:13:41.179
how to use brand.yaml, thematic already knows how to hook into the theming things that BSLib

00:13:41.179 --> 00:13:49.260
does, and so if you were using thematic in an R markdown document or in a Shiny app,

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:57.340
you basically can have your plots themed, your ggplot plots themed to match your brand.yaml

00:13:57.340 --> 00:14:01.340
just by turning on thematic, which is pretty awesome.

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:08.299
And the Shiny for R app in the repository that I showed in the demo does use thematic,

00:14:08.299 --> 00:14:10.619
so you can take a look at that.

00:14:10.619 --> 00:14:16.260
I did have to do a slight bit of extra tweaking, but it mostly just themed it correctly right

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:19.260
off the bat.

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:21.179
Awesome.

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:27.940
So I think that then answers Mike's question in the chat.

00:14:27.940 --> 00:14:32.219
So, yes, it works with ggplot theming.

00:14:32.219 --> 00:14:35.179
Brittany asks a great question.

00:14:35.179 --> 00:14:39.739
How do you recommend sharing brand.yaml files across an organisation?

00:14:39.739 --> 00:14:42.260
This is a really good question.

00:14:42.260 --> 00:14:48.739
Again, the answer will be a little different depending on if you want to use it for Shiny

00:14:48.739 --> 00:14:55.340
and for Quarto, which are the two systems that use brand.yaml right now.

00:14:55.340 --> 00:15:01.900
There's a way to share a brand.yaml file through a Quarto extension, right?

00:15:01.900 --> 00:15:08.140
So someone else just asked an extension question, so I'll follow up on that too.

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:13.059
And so there's a way for you to create an extension that packages the brand.yaml file.

00:15:13.059 --> 00:15:17.020
So if someone wants to use a brand.yaml file, they can just Quarto add an extension and

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:22.299
then extension will pick up the brand.yaml configuration in Quarto projects.

00:15:22.299 --> 00:15:28.099
We haven't given a concrete example out there, like in our blog or something, so you have

00:15:28.099 --> 00:15:32.099
to know the trick to do it, but it's possible to do today.

00:15:32.099 --> 00:15:36.380
We're soon going to post something on like a blog or documentation on how to do that

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:38.700
because it's a very important, very common question.

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:40.700
So that's as far as Quarto is concerned.

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:44.619
So before, sorry, Jarek, just to answer the question of whether this will replace the

00:15:44.619 --> 00:15:48.580
extension folder, Quarto extensions are used for more things than just brand, right?

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:52.340
So you can create filters, you can create article formats, you can create a lot of other

00:15:52.340 --> 00:15:57.940
things. So it's not that it will replace an extension format, it's that you can create an

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:02.059
extension in Quarto that will bring in the brand and then it will just work.

00:16:02.059 --> 00:16:03.380
It will have the branding for that.

00:16:06.820 --> 00:16:13.820
And on the Shiny side, we have definitely, so there's sort of like the easy case, which

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:18.059
is you just put your brand.yaml file inside, like in the same place as your app and then it

00:16:18.059 --> 00:16:20.580
just works sort of like Quarto does as well.

00:16:21.340 --> 00:16:26.739
But there are also, you know, all of the functions that sort of bring in brand.yaml

00:16:26.739 --> 00:16:33.179
files take a path as an argument or let you specify where the brand.yaml file lives.

00:16:33.539 --> 00:16:39.140
And at that point, it could be anywhere as far as Shiny or R Markdown is concerned.

00:16:40.780 --> 00:16:46.299
Personally, if I were in charge of maintaining a brand.yaml, I would probably create a

00:16:46.299 --> 00:16:50.580
small repo that has just the brand.yaml file and the extra assets.

00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:55.500
You know, you end up with some logos and some other, maybe some, you know, fonts next to

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:57.979
the brand.yaml. And I'd probably just put that all in a small repo.

00:16:57.979 --> 00:17:04.979
And in the future, I can see us adding tooling that makes it easier to go grab all of

00:17:04.979 --> 00:17:08.420
those things from a repo or from somewhere.

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:14.420
Mike pointed out a question about using, use this for that, right?

00:17:14.420 --> 00:17:17.979
Sort of like just use branding and then you point at a file or you point to the repository

00:17:17.979 --> 00:17:20.660
or something. So that is something we could we could do.

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:23.900
We haven't done yet, but that's very naturally a thing that makes sense to do.

00:17:24.859 --> 00:17:30.219
The part that, again, needs a little bit of care is that Quarto uses brand.yaml

00:17:30.219 --> 00:17:34.099
configuration, Shiny uses brand.yaml configuration, and we hope other systems and

00:17:34.099 --> 00:17:35.579
libraries will use this in the future.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:39.140
So each one of these might have a slightly different way of like pulling in that

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:43.979
information. And so it's sort of like it wouldn't be exactly use branding.

00:17:43.979 --> 00:17:47.459
It would be like, you know, use Shiny branding or use Quarto branding or something of that

00:17:47.459 --> 00:17:50.579
sort, because these details might make a difference.

00:17:50.579 --> 00:17:55.300
So we want to be a little careful on how to do these general use this.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:18:00.579
So we'll probably take a little bit of time to let sort of the use patterns show up in a

00:18:00.579 --> 00:18:04.540
way that's natural. And then once we understand them well, we will put them inside use

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:07.939
this. So I expect that kind of thing to come up, Mike.

00:18:07.939 --> 00:18:11.020
It's a very good question, but it will not be in the immediate future.

00:18:11.020 --> 00:18:15.579
We still need to sort of understand a little better how the community is going to use

00:18:15.579 --> 00:18:16.219
brand.yaml.

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:25.099
Thank you. See, John had asked a question during the demo as well, and it was would also

00:18:25.099 --> 00:18:31.060
be interested to know if you can use these.yaml files outside of the directory for our

00:18:31.060 --> 00:18:34.900
dashboards or apps so multiple projects can point to the same file.

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:40.219
Yeah, and I'll say that, yes, you totally can do this.

00:18:41.099 --> 00:18:47.020
I think ultimately you will end up running into the small problem of when you go to

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:51.540
deploy your shiny apps, you'll likely want to have all of the files be contained in the

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:56.900
same folder. In general, lots of deployment patterns require that.

00:18:57.180 --> 00:19:04.260
But beyond that, you know, locally or or, yeah, the shiny, at least on the shiny side,

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:10.180
things are pretty flexible in the sense of, you know, we try to like nudge you towards

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:14.660
keeping all of your app files in the same folder, but you could have a shared directory

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:16.939
where you put your brand.yaml and you could use that.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:24.619
Yeah, quarto is a little more opinionated about this, you will need to put your brand

00:19:24.619 --> 00:19:29.459
file in the quarto directory, your brand.yaml configuration in the quarto project

00:19:29.459 --> 00:19:34.619
configuration. You can have subdirectors of your quarto project that all share a single

00:19:34.619 --> 00:19:37.020
brand.yaml file that totally works.

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:38.780
That's sort of the standard way to do that.

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:43.140
But separate projects need to have sort of separate files.

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:44.780
That's what we use extensions for.

00:19:45.540 --> 00:19:47.859
The reason we do this is for reproducibility, right?

00:19:47.859 --> 00:19:52.140
It's sort of for deployment, like Garrick is saying, the risk of doing something outside of

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:54.260
the directory is that you no longer control it.

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:58.219
So if someone else changes it, now things can change in your project and you don't see it.

00:19:58.219 --> 00:20:02.260
And that makes it really hard for you to track down and maintain it sort of, you know, it's

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:08.060
very convenient for like five projects, but it's really, really complicated and hard when

00:20:08.060 --> 00:20:10.020
you get to like 25 or 30 projects.

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:13.060
Right. So we just take the conservative approach and ask you to put things inside the

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:13.579
directory.

00:20:16.099 --> 00:20:18.540
Thank you. Another question.

00:20:19.579 --> 00:20:25.060
And people are testing my pronunciation with packages, but is brandy compatible with a

00:20:25.060 --> 00:20:30.579
sharing gun or can it also be used with quarto documents in shiny apps?

00:20:31.579 --> 00:20:33.699
I think presentations.

00:20:34.380 --> 00:20:40.900
Yeah, I love I love sharing and I happen to also maintain a package called sharing in

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:47.099
femur and the which is designed to create full sharing themes.

00:20:47.739 --> 00:20:51.459
And I appreciate the nudge.

00:20:51.459 --> 00:20:54.180
I feel like brandy ammo would be a great fit for that.

00:20:54.180 --> 00:20:55.500
And it would totally work.

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:59.819
And it could be a new feature in the sharing and femur package.

00:21:01.579 --> 00:21:06.780
But but it wasn't actually something that was on my mind until now.

00:21:06.819 --> 00:21:13.699
So thank you. That being said, you know, you can grab you can use the idea, as Carlos had

00:21:13.699 --> 00:21:19.780
said before, is that brandy ammo is this is a first and foremost, it's a specification or

00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:23.180
structure for organizing information about your brand.

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:30.140
So the in other words, you could use the brandy ammo file and read it and pull out the

00:21:30.140 --> 00:21:33.579
fields that you need and pass them to sharing and femur.

00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:39.660
And just about anywhere that brandy ammo doesn't currently work by magic, it can be made

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:43.060
to work using normal theming ideas.

00:21:43.060 --> 00:21:49.380
So there's always the escape hatch of just taking the stuff that's in your brandy ammo

00:21:49.380 --> 00:21:56.099
file and passing it to the appropriate theming functions or or finding something that

00:21:56.099 --> 00:21:56.859
can help you do that.

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:05.459
Thank you, and I want to make sure I share the GitHub remote repo for brandy ammo in the

00:22:05.459 --> 00:22:06.660
chat here as well.

00:22:07.339 --> 00:22:10.420
Thank you, Carlos, for reminding me about that.

00:22:10.819 --> 00:22:15.300
So that's the like, Eric said, that's the specification documentation, right?

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:21.380
So that's sort of like what he and I worked on that explains how to organize the

00:22:21.939 --> 00:22:27.780
information on these files so that Quarto and Shiny and in the future, Zaring and thematic

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:31.619
and ggplot can all get the information from this.

00:22:31.619 --> 00:22:36.900
Right. But generally speaking, different packages, different systems, different libraries

00:22:36.900 --> 00:22:40.900
will need to learn to speak brandy ammo.

00:22:40.900 --> 00:22:42.420
So to speak, right.

00:22:42.420 --> 00:22:44.260
Like that's not something that happens automatically.

